Here's an example of blocking read interrupted by signal, with EINTR handling:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <sys/stat.h>
#include <fcntl.h>
#include <signal.h>

#define BUF_SIZE 1024

void handle_signal(int signum) {
    printf("Signal received: %d\n", signum);
    exit(EXIT_SUCCESS);
}

int main() {
    int fd;
    char *buf = malloc(BUF_SIZE);
    struct stat stat_buf;
    ssize_t num_read;

    if ((fd = open("file.txt", O_RDONLY)) == -1) {
        perror("open");
        exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
    }

    if (fstat(fd, &stat_buf) == -1) {
        perror("fstat");
        exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
    }

    if (signal(SIGINT, handle_signal) == SIG_ERR) {
        perror("signal");
        exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
    }

    while ((num_read = read(fd, buf, BUF_SIZE)) > 0) {
        printf("Read %zd bytes: %s\n", num_read, buf);
    }

    if (num_read == -1) {
        perror("read");
        exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
    }

    close(fd);
    free(buf);

    exit(EXIT_SUCCESS);
}
```

In this example, we use the `read()` system call to read data from a file. We also use the `signal()` system call to handle the `SIGINT` signal, which is sent when the user presses the interrupt key (usually Ctrl+C).

When the `SIGINT` signal is received, the `handle_signal()` function is called. This function simply prints a message indicating that the signal was received, and then exits the program.

In the main loop of the program, we use the `read()` system call to read data from the file. If the `read()` system call is interrupted by the `SIGINT` signal, the system call will return with a value of -1, and the `errno` variable will be set to the value of `EINTR`.

To handle the `EINTR` error, we simply check the return value of the `read()` system call. If the return value is -1, we check the value of the `errno` variable. If the value of `errno` is `EINTR`, we simply continue with the next iteration of the loop. Otherwise, we print an error message and exit the program.

