Yes, it is possible to implement TCP in TypeScript. Here is an example implementation:

```typescript
class TcpConnection {
  private socket: any;
  private buffer: Buffer;
  private sequenceNumber: number;
  private ackNumber: number;
  private windowSize: number;
  private state: string;
  private remoteAddress: string;
  private remotePort: number;

  constructor(socket: any) {
    this.socket = socket;
    this.buffer = new Buffer(65535);
    this.sequenceNumber = 0;
    this.ackNumber = 0;
    this.windowSize = 65535;
    this.state = 'CLOSED';
    this.remoteAddress = '';
    this.remotePort = 0;
  }

  public async connect(address: string, port: number): Promise<void> {
    this.remoteAddress = address;
    this.remotePort = port;

    await this.socket.connect(address, port);
  }

  public async send(data: Buffer): Promise<void> {
    const sequenceNumber = this.sequenceNumber++;
    const packet = new Buffer(4 + data.length);
    packet.writeUInt32BE(sequenceNumber, 0);
    packet.write(data, 4);

    await this.socket.write(packet);
  }

  public async receive(): Promise<Buffer> {
    const buffer = new Buffer(65535);
    const bytesRead = await this.socket.read(buffer);
    if (bytesRead === 0) {
      return null;
    }

    const packet = buffer.slice(0, bytesRead);
    const sequenceNumber = packet.readUInt32BE(0);
    const ackNumber = packet.readUInt32BE(4);
    const data = packet.slice(8);

    this.sequenceNumber = sequenceNumber + 1;
    this.ackNumber = ackNumber + 1;

    return data;
  }
}

export default TcpConnection;
```

This implementation uses the `net.Socket` class from Node.js to handle the underlying TCP socket. The `TcpConnection` class provides a higher-level API for sending and receiving data over the TCP connection.

