Here's an example C# program that sends a POST request with a client certificate attached:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Net;
using System.Security.Cryptography.X509Certificates;
using System.Text;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

namespace PostRequestWithClientCert
{
    class Program
    {
        static async Task Main(string[] args)
        {
            // Set up the client certificate
            X509Certificate2 clientCert = new X509Certificate2("client.pfx", "password");

            // Set up the POST request
            string url = "https://example.com/api";
            string data = "param1=value1&param2=value2";
            string contentType = "application/x-www-form-urlencoded";

            // Set up the HTTP client
            HttpClient httpClient = new HttpClient();
            httpClient.DefaultRequestHeaders.Add("User-Agent", "PostRequestWithClientCert/1.0");

            // Attach the client certificate to the request
            httpClient.ClientCertificates.Add(clientCert);

            // Send the POST request
            HttpResponseMessage response = await httpClient.PostAsync(url, new StringContent(data, Encoding.UTF8, contentType));

            // Check the response status code
            if (response.IsSuccessStatusCode)
            {
                Console.WriteLine("POST request with client certificate sent successfully.");
            }
            else
            {
                Console.WriteLine("POST request with client certificate failed with status code: " + response.StatusCode);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Here's a simple C# function that extracts all hashtags from a given text:

```csharp
public static List<string> ExtractHashtags(string text)
{
    List<string> hashtags = new List<string>();

    foreach (string word in text.Split(' '))
    {
        if (word.StartsWith("#"))
        {
            string hashtag = word.Remove(0, 1);
            hashtags.Add(hashtag);
        }
    }

    return hashtags;
}
```

This function takes a string as input and returns a list of all hashtags found in the text. The function uses the `Split` method to split the input text into individual words, and then loops through each word to check if it starts with a "#" character. If it does, the function removes the "#" character from the beginning of the word, and adds the resulting hashtag to the list of hashtags. Finally, the function returns the list of hashtags.

